==Invitation and team selection==
The [[1980 Summer Olympics]] in [[Moscow]], the capital of the [[Soviet Union]], were the first to include a [[field hockey at the 1980 Summer Olympics|competition]] in women's [[field hockey]].{{#tag:ref|Men's field hockey first appeared at the Olympics in [[1908 Summer Olympics|1908]] and has been played continuously since [[1928 Summer Olympics|1928]].{{sfn|Mallon|Heijmans|2011|p=156}}|group="n"|name="mens"}} Pre-tournament favourites included [[Australia women's national field hockey team|Australia]], the [[Netherlands women's national field hockey team|Netherlands]] and [[Germany women's national field hockey team|West Germany]], but the [[1980 Summer Olympics boycott|American-led Western boycott]] of the Moscow Olympics led to these teams and others withdrawing, leaving only the Soviets in the women's hockey event. The Soviet and international Olympic authorities filled the gaps by inviting teams from countries that had not qualified.{{sfn|Harris|2008 a}} Among the nations invited was Zimbabwe, which had become an internationally recognised country in April 1980 following seven years of [[Rhodesian Bush War|civil war]]. Moscow marked the southern African nation's [[Zimbabwe at the 1980 Summer Olympics|return to the Olympics]] after 16 years; as [[Rhodesia]] it had been excluded from the [[1968 Summer Olympics|1968]], [[1972 Summer Olympics|1972]] and [[1976 Summer Olympics|1976]] Games for political reasons following the mostly [[white people in Zimbabwe|white]] government's [[Rhodesia's Unilateral Declaration of Independence|declaration of independence]] from Britain in 1965.{{sfn|Little|2005}} The Zimbabwe Olympic Committee received the invitation to send men's and women's hockey squads to Moscow on 14 June 1980, 35 days before the Olympics were due to start.{{sfn|Zimbabwe Olympic Committee}} They were taken totally by surprise—they had not prepared hockey teams for the Games—but nevertheless agreed to send a [[Zimbabwe women's national field hockey team|wom