==Reactions and legacy== [[File:Sally Hayfron.jpg|thumb|upright|[[Sally Hayfron|Sally Mugabe]] promised each of the players an ox, but ultimately gave them packages of meat instead.|alt=A woman in a yellow and green African-style dress smiles]]
The victorious hockey players were immediately dubbed the "Golden Girls" by Zimbabwean reporters.{{sfn|Byrom|McDermott|Streak|1980|pp=249–253}} They were greeted by huge crowds on their return to Zimbabwe and briefly became national celebrities.{{sfn|Harris|2008 b}} Prime Minister [[Robert Mugabe]] welcomed them home at an official function. Each member of the team was promised an ox by the Prime Minister's wife [[Sally Hayfron|Sally]], but ultimately received a polystyrene package of meat instead at a ceremony hosted by Mrs Mugabe.{{sfn|Harris|2008 a}} Many of the players emigrated over the following years, mostly to South Africa.{{sfn|Harris|2008 a}} Their victory continues to be celebrated in Zimbabwe today.<ref>{{Harvnb|Chirumanzu|2012}}; {{Harvnb|Daily News|2012}}.</ref> The country did not win another Olympic medal until [[Kirsty Coventry]] won three swimming medals in [[Athens]] in [[2004 Summer Olympics|2004]].{{sfn|Sandu|Muchinjo|2004}} Robert Mugabe promptly applied the "golden girl" nickname to her on her return home.{{sfn|Mathers|2010}}
The Zimbabwean hockey team's victory at the 1980 Olympics was widely considered a great [[upset]]. Sports historians have called it a "fairytale"{{sfn|Harris|2008 a}} and an "irresistible fairy story".{{sfn|Tomlinson|2010|p=239}} While the Zimbabweans were overjoyed by their unlikely status as the first ever Olympic gold medallists in women's hockey, some, including Robert Sullivan of ''[[Sports Illustrated]]'', felt that the Zimbabwean victory epitomised how the Western boycott had lowered competitive standards and, in their opinion, "ruined" the 1980 Olympics.{{sfn|Sullivan|1984}} While acknowledging this to an extent, Cathy Harris asserted in her 2008 retrospective on the team, published in ''[[The Sunday Times]]'', that the victory still deserved to be recognised as a great achievement. "They freely acknowledge that they won the gold medal without competing against the best in the world", she concludes, "but, like many athletes in Moscow in 1980, they seized their chance."{{sfn|Harris|2008 a}}
