[[Category:Field hockey at the 1980 Summer Olympics]] [[Category:Field hockey in Zimbabwe]] [[Category:History of Zimbabwe]] [[Category:National sports teams of Zimbabwe]] [[Category:Olympic field hockey players of Zimbabwe]] [[Category:Olympic gold medalists for Zimbabwe]] [[Category:Women's national field hockey teams]] [[Category:Zimbabwe at the Olympics]]

{{featured article}} [[File:RIAN archive 556180 Women's field hockey team from Zimbabwe.jpg|thumb|300px|The Zimbabweans celebrate after their 4–0 win over Poland at [[Dynamo Minor Arena (Moscow)|Dynamo Minor Arena]], Moscow.|alt=Women in hockey attire celebrate, waving their arms and sticks in the air]] The 1980 [[Zimbabwe women's national field hockey team]] won the gold medal in women's [[field hockey]] at that year's [[1980 Summer Olympics|Summer Olympics]] in [[Moscow]], the capital of the [[Soviet Union]]. The squad of 16 women, all from [[Zimbabwe]]'s [[white people in Zimbabwe|white]] minority, was assembled less than a month before the Olympics began to help fill the gaps the American-led [[1980 Summer Olympics boycott|Olympic boycott]] created in the [[field hockey at the 1980 Summer Olympics|women's hockey competition]]. Zimbabwe's subsequent victory in the [[round-robin tournament]] with three wins and two draws was regarded as a huge [[upset]], particularly considering the team's lack of preparation and experience; it has been called an "irresistible fairy story".{{sfn|Tomlinson|2010|p=239}} Won at a time of great political transition in Zimbabwe, the gold medal was the country's first Olympic medal of any colour.
The 1980 Olympics were first to feature women's hockey, and the first to include Zimbabwe under that name—barred from the last three Olympics for political reasons, the country had last competed as [[Rhodesia]] in [[Rhodesia at the 1964 Summer Olympics|1964]]. The women's hockey matches, held between 25 and 31 July, were all played on [[artificial turf]], which none of the Zimbabwean team members had ever seen; they had also never played together until that month. After beating [[Poland women's national field hockey team|Poland]] and the [[Soviet Union women's national field hockey team|USSR]] and drawing with [[Czechoslovakia women's national field hockey team|Czechoslovakia]] and [[India women's national field hockey team|India]], the Zimbabweans won the competition on the final day with a 4–1 victory over [[Austria women's national field hockey team|Austria]]. Dubbed the "Golden Girls" by the [[media of Zimbabwe]], they were met by cheering crowds on their return home, and were briefly national celebrities. Zimbabwe did not win another Olympic medal until 2004.
==Invitation and team selection== The [[1980 Summer Olympics]] in Moscow, the capital of the [[Soviet Union]], were the first to include a [[field hockey at the 1980 Summer Olympics|competition]] in women's [[field hockey]].{{refn|Men's field hockey first appeared at the Olympics in [[1908 Summer Olympics|1908]] and has been played continuously since [[1928 Summer Olympics|1928]].{{sfn|Mallon|Heijmans|2011|p=156}}|group="n"|name="mens"}} Pre-tournament favourites included [[Australia women's national field hockey team|Australia]], the [[Netherlands women's national field hockey team|Netherlands]] and [[Germany women's national field hockey team|West Germany]], but the [[1980 Summer Olympics boycott|American-led Western boycott]] of the Moscow Olympics led to these teams and others withdrawing, leaving only the Soviets in the women's hockey event. The Soviet and international Olympic authorities filled the gaps by inviting teams from countries that had not qualified.{{sfn|Harris|2008 a}} Among the nations invited was Zimbabwe, which had become an internationally recognised country in April 1980 following seven years of [[Rhodesian Bush War|civil war]]. Moscow marked the southern African nation's [[Zimbabwe at the 1980 Summer Olympics|return to the Olympics]] after 16 years; as [[Rhodesia]] it had been excluded from the [[1968 Summer Olympics|1968]], [[1972 Summer Olympics|1972]] and [[1976 Summer Olympics|1976]] Games for political reasons following the mostly [[white people in Zimbabwe|white]] government's [[Rhodesia's Unilateral Declaration of Independence|declaration of independence]] from Britain in 1965.{{sfn|Little|2005}} The Zimbabwe Olympic Committee received the invitation to send men's and women's hockey squads to Moscow on 14 June 1980, 35 days before the Olympics were due to start.{{sfn|Zimbabwe Olympic Committee}} They were taken totally by surprise—they had not prepared hockey teams for the Games—but nevertheless agreed to send a [[Zimbabwe women's national field hockey team|women's squad]].{{sfn|Harris|2008 a}} No women's hockey team representing the country had ever played overseas before.{{sfn|Zimbabwe Olympic Committee}}
A squad of 16 members, built around the core of the former Rhodesia team,{{sfn|Harris|2008 a}} was hastily assembled by Liz Dreyer, the president of the national women's hockey association, who became the team's manager. Every player and official was white.{{sfn|Harris|2008 a}} [[Ann Grant]], the team's 25-year-old sweeper, was appointed captain. [[Anthea Stewart]], who had played for [[South Africa women's national field hockey team|South Africa]] 25 times before retiring in 1974, both coached the squad and played herself. [[Liz Chase]], the only other team member with international experience (having also represented South Africa) was made vice-captain. At 35 years old, Stewart was the team's oldest player, while [[Arlene Boxall]], the 18-year-old reserve goalkeeper, was the youngest. The squad included twin sisters in [[Sandra Chick|Sandy Chick]] and [[Sonia Robertson]].{{sfn|Zimbabwe Olympic Committee}}
Entirely amateur, the team mostly comprised players with professions unrelated to sport—Grant, for example, was a bookkeeper, while Boxall was an operations clerk in the [[Air Force of Zimbabwe]].{{sfn|Zimbabwe Olympic Committee}} Several had sporting relatives, most prominently Grant, whose brother was the international cricketer [[Duncan Fletcher]].{{sfn|Harris|2008 a}} Audrey Palmer, a seasoned hockey official and referee who had played for Rhodesia from 1953 to 1961, travelled with the team as a medic, trainer and general supervisor.{{sfn|Zimbabwe Olympic Committee}} The squad left on 7 July, travelling first to the Zambian capital [[Lusaka]] and then to [[Luanda]] in Angola,{{sfn|Caute|1983|p=438}} from where they flew to Moscow on an aircraft usually used for freighting meat. "The stench was terrible", Grant later said. "There were no seats, so we all sat on the floor, strapped in and set off into the unknown. We didn't even have the right shoes to play on the [[artificial turf|artificial hockey surface]]."{{sfn|Harris|2008 a}}
{| class="wikitable sortable" border="1" style="text-align:left" |+ 1980 Zimbabwe women's national field hockey team{{sfn|Zimbabwe Olympic Committee}} ! Name ''(role)'' ! Position ! Date of birth (age) ! Profession ! Club |- | {{sortname|Arlene|Boxall}} | Goalkeeper | {{sort|18|9 October 1961 (age 18)}} | Operations clerk in Air Force of Zimbabwe | Police |- | {{sortname|Liz|Chase}} ''(vice-captain)'' | Forward | {{sort|30|26 April 1950 (age 30)}} | Physical education teacher | Old Hararians |- | {{sortname|Sandra|Chick}} | Forward | {{sort|33|2 June 1947 (age 33)}} | Bank official | Salisbury Sports |- | {{sortname|Gillian|Cowley}} | Various | {{sort|25|8 July 1955 (age 25)}} | Bookkeeper | Salisbury Sports |- | {{sortname|Patricia|Davies}} | Various | {{sort|23|5 December 1956 (age 23)}} | Secretary | Old Hararians |- | {{sortname|Sarah|English}} | Goalkeeper | {{sort|24|28 November 1955 (age 24)}} | Audit clerk | [[Queens Sports Club]] |- | {{sortname|Maureen|George}} | Defender | {{sort|24|1 September 1955 (age 24)}} | Secretary | Salisbury Sports |- | {{sortname|Ann|Grant}} ''(captain)'' | Sweeper | {{sort|25|6 May 1955 (age 25)}} | Bookkeeper | Old Hararians |- | {{sortname|Susan|Huggett}} | Various | {{sort|26|29 June 1954 (age 26)}} | Bookkeeper | Old Hararians |- | {{sortname|Patricia|McKillop}} | Midfielder | {{sort|24|15 July 1956 (age 24)}} | Housewife | Bulawayo Athletic Club |- | {{sortname|Brenda|Phillips}} | Midfielder | {{sort|22|18 January 1958 (age 22)}} | Physical education teacher | Old Miltonians |- | {{sortname|Christine|Prinsloo}} | Midfielder | {{sort|28|3 May 1952 (age 28)}} | Insurance underwriter | Salisbury Postals |- | {{sortname|Sonia|Robertson}} | Defender | {{sort|33|2 June 1947 (age 33)}} | Sports coach | Salisbury Sports |- | {{sortname|Anthea|Stewart}} ''(player-coach)'' | Various | {{sort|35|20 November 1944 (age 35)}} | ''Not recorded'' |align=center|— |- | {{sortname|Helen|Volk}} | Various | {{sort|26|29 March 1954 (age 26)}} |