{{good article}} [[File:RIAN archive 556180 Women's field hockey team from Zimbabwe.jpg|thumb|300px|The Zimbabweans celebrate after their 4–0 win over Poland at [[Dynamo Minor Arena (Moscow)|Dynamo Minor Arena]], Moscow]] The 1980 [[Zimbabwe women's national field hockey team]] won the gold medal in women's [[field hockey]] at that year's [[1980 Summer Olympics|Summer Olympics]] in [[Moscow]], [[Soviet Union|USSR]]. The squad of 16 women, all from Zimbabwe's [[white people in Zimbabwe|white]] minority, was assembled less than a month before the Olympics began to help fill the gaps the U.S.-led [[1980 Summer Olympics boycott|Olympic boycott]] created in the [[field hockey at the 1980 Summer Olympics|women's field hockey competition]]. Zimbabwe's subsequent undefeated victory in the [[round-robin tournament]] with three wins and two draws was widely regarded as a huge [[upset]], particularly considering the team's lack of preparation and experience; it has been called an "irresistible fairy story".{{sfn|Tomlinson|2010|p=239}} Won at a time of great political transition in Zimbabwe, the gold medal was the country's first of any colour at the Olympics.
The 1980 Olympics were first to feature women's field hockey, and also the first to include Zimbabwe under that name—barred from the last three Olympics for political reasons, the country had last competed as [[Rhodesia]] in [[Rhodesia at the 1964 Summer Olympics|1964]]. The women's hockey matches, held between 25 and 31 July, were all played on [[artificial turf]], which none of the Zimbabwean team members had ever seen; they had also never played together until that month. After beating [[Poland women's national field hockey team|Poland]] and the [[Soviet Union women's national field hockey team|USSR]] and drawing with [[Czechoslovakia women's national field hockey team|Czechoslovakia]] and [[India women's national field hockey team|India]], the Zimbabweans won the competition on the final day with a 4–1 victory over [[Austria women's national field hockey team|Austria]]. Dubbed the "Golden Girls" by the Zimbabwean press, they were met by cheering crowds on their return home, and were briefly national celebrities. Zimbabwe did not win another Olympic medal until 2004.
==Invitation and team selection==
The [[1980 Summer Olympics]] in [[Moscow]], the capital of the [[Soviet Union]], were the first to include a [[field hockey at the 1980 Summer Olympics|competition]] in women's [[field hockey]].{{#tag:ref|Men's field hockey first appeared at the Olympics in [[1908 Summer Olympics|1908]] and has been played continuously since [[1928 Summer Olympics|1928]].{{sfn|Mallon|Heijmans|2011|p=156}}|group="n"|name="mens"}} Pre-tournament favourites included [[Australia women's national field hockey team|Australia]], the [[Netherlands women's national field hockey team|Netherlands]] and [[Germany women's national field hockey team|West Germany]], but the [[1980 Summer Olympics boycott|U.S.-led Western boycott]] of the Moscow Olympics led to these teams and others withdrawing, leaving only the Soviets in the women's hockey event. The Soviet and international Olympic authorities filled the gaps by inviting teams from countries that had not qualified.{{sfn|Harris|2008 a}} Among the nations invited was Zimbabwe, which had just become an internationally recognised country in April 1980 following seven years of [[Rhodesian Bush War|civil war]]. Moscow marked the southern African nation's [[Zimbabwe at the 1980 Summer Olympics|return to the Olympics]] after 16 years; as [[Rhodesia]] it had been excluded from the [[1968 Summer Olympics|1968]], [[1972 Summer Olympics|1972]] and [[1976 Summer Olympics|1976]] Games for political reasons.{{sfn|Little|2005}} The Zimbabwe Olympic Committee received the invitation to send men's and women's hockey squads to Moscow on 14 June 1980, just 35 days before the Olympics were due to start.{{sfn|Zimbabwe Olympic Committee}} They were taken totally by surprise—they had not prepared hockey teams for the Games—but nevertheless agreed to organise and send a [[Zimbabwe women's national field hockey team|women's squad]].{{sfn|Harris|2008 a}} No women's hockey team representing the country had ever played overseas before.{{sfn|Zimbabwe Olympic Committee}}
